Mirror the established .AsEnumerable() remediation used elsewhere in this same file (line 2271) and in MyReports. Pull the EF-translatable joins+where into an IQueryable, cross an .AsEnumerable() boundary, then compute the per-row collections client-side so output is identical.

Concretely in GetHireReturn (lines 170-232): keep `qs` and `mc` lets (they are scalar FirstOrDefault subqueries EF Core CAN translate and are used in the `where`), but REMOVE the three collection lets (app/AppStatus/chkAppStatus) from the server query. Change the base query to select the translatable columns plus `b.HireReturnId` (already present), apply the existing `where`, then append `.AsEnumerable()` (or `.ToList()`) BEFORE building app/AppStatus/chkAppStatus. After the boundary, compute per row:
  app = db.Approvals.Where(x => x.TransEntry == row.HireReturnId && x.Type == "HireReturn").Select(x => x.EmployeeId).ToList();
  AppStatus = db.ApprovalUpdates.Where(x => x.TransEntry == row.HireReturnId && x.Type == "HireReturn").Select(x => x.ApprovalStatus).ToList();
  chkAppStatus = db.ApprovalUpdates.Where(x => x.TransEntry == row.HireReturnId && x.Type == "HireReturn").AsEnumerable().GroupBy(l => l.ApprovedBy).Select(g => g.OrderByDescending(c => c.CreatedDate).First()).Select(x => x.ApprovalStatus).ToList();

Minimal-diff alternative that preserves the existing single LINQ block exactly: insert `.AsEnumerable()` on the OUTER source so the whole `select new {...}` (with the three lets) runs in LINQ-to-Objects, AND add `.AsEnumerable()` before the inner GroupBy in chkAppStatus. I.e. change `from b in db.HireReturns` to `from b in db.HireReturns.AsEnumerable()` is NOT enough (the joins/where still need server eval and AsEnumerable() on the table pulls all HireReturns into memory â€” acceptable functionally and matches the legacy client-eval semantics, but for performance prefer pushing the where server-side first). Recommended: keep joins+where server-side selecting scalar columns + HireReturnId, call .AsEnumerable(), then build the three lists per row as above. This is output-preserving (identical app/AppStatus/chkAppStatus lists and the downstream Approval/ApprovalStatus computation at lines 255-256 are unchanged) and matches the legacy EF6 client-evaluated behavior. Note: after .AsEnumerable(), change the EF.Functions.DateDiffDay calls in the where to client-side date comparisons, or keep the where on the IQueryable side before .AsEnumerable() (preferred) so those still translate.
